<subsection xml:id="subsec-multiplication-of-vector-by-a-scalar">
    <title>Multiplication of Vector by a Scalar</title>
    <activity>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in groups</alert>
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    On a graph paper, draw the <m>x</m> axis and <m>y</m> axis.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Draw a directed line passing through point <m>A(0,2)</m> and <m>B(2,2)</m>, and label it as vector <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    From point <m>B(2,2)</m>, draw another directed line to point <m>C(4,2)</m>, and label it as vector <m>\overrightarrow{BC}</m>. 
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Determine the coordinate representations of <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{AC}</m>..
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    How does <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> relate to <m>\overrightarrow{AC}</m>?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Discuss and share your findings with the rest of the class.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <p>
        <term>Positive Scalar</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        In <xref ref="multiplication-vectors-scalar"/>, the vector <m>PQ</m> is represented
        as <m>\mathbf{a}</m>.
        When we multiply <m>\mathbf{a}</m> by a positive scalar, say <m>2</m>,
        the length of the vector doubles, making it <m>\mathbf{2a}</m>. 
        The direction of the vector remains unchanged, but its magnitude increases.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="multiplication-vectors-scalar">
        <caption></caption>
        <image width="30%">
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>  
            <latex-image>  
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                    
                    \draw[thick,-|] (0,0) -- (2,0);
                    \draw[thick,|-] (2,0) -- (4,0);
                    \node[left] at (0,0) {$\mathbf{P}$};
                    \node[right] at (4,0) {$\mathbf{Q}$};
                    \node at (2.5,0.3) {$\mathbf{a}$};
                    
                    % Draw arrows at the middle of the lines
                    %\draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (-1,1) -- (0,2);
                    \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (2,0) -- (2.3,0);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image> 
        </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
        In <xref ref="multiplication-vectors-scalar-1"/>, the vector <m>\mathbf{PN}</m> is given by:
        <m>\mathbf{PN} = \mathbf{a} + \mathbf{a} = 2\mathbf{a}</m>.
        This means <m>\mathbf{PN}</m> has the same direction as <m>\mathbf{PN}</m>, and its magnitude
        twice that of <m>\mathbf{PQ}.</m>
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="multiplication-vectors-scalar-1">
        <caption></caption>
        <image width="70%">
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>  
            <latex-image>  
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                    
                    \draw[thick,|-] (0,0) -- (2,0);
                    \draw[thick,-|] (2,0) -- (4,0);

                    \draw[thick,|-] (4,0) -- (6,0);
                    \draw[thick,-|] (6,0) -- (8,0);

                    %\draw[thick,|-] (8,0) -- (10,0);
                    %\draw[thick,-|] (10,0) -- (12,0);

                    \node[below] at (0,0) {$\mathbf{P}$};
                    \node[below] at (4,0) {$\mathbf{Q}$};
                    \node[below] at (8,0) {$\mathbf{N}$};

                    \node at (2.5,0.3) {$\mathbf{a}$};
                    \node at (6.5,0.3) {$\mathbf{a}$};
                    %\node at (10.5,0.3) {$\mathbf{a}$};
                    
                    % Draw arrows at the middle of the lines
                    \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (2,0) -- (2.3,0);
                    \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (6,0) -- (6.3,0);
                    %\draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (10,0) -- (10.3,0);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image> 
        </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
        <term>Negative Scalar</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        Consider the vector <m>\mathbf{PQ}</m>,denoted as <m>\mathbf{a}</m>, in <xref ref="multiplication-vectors-negative-scalar-1"/>
        The vector points to the right and has a magnitude of <m>\mathbf{a}</m>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="multiplication-vectors-negative-scalar-1">
        <caption></caption>
        <image width="50%">
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>  
            <latex-image>  
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                    
                    \draw[thick,|-|] (0,0) -- (4,0);

                    \node[below] at (0,0) {$\mathbf{P}$};
                    \node[below] at (4,0) {$\mathbf{Q}$};

                    \node at (2,0.4) {$\mathbf{a}$};
                    
                    % Draw arrows at the middle of the lines
                    \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (2,0) -- (2.3,0);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image> 
        </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
        In <xref ref="multiplication-vectors-negative-scalar-2"/>, the 
        vector <m>\mathbf{PN}</m> is obtained by multiplying <m>\mathbf{PQ}</m>
        by <m>-2</m>, giving:
    </p>
    <p>
        <me>
            \mathbf{PN} = \mathbf{-2} \times \mathbf{a} = \mathbf{-2a}
        </me>
        
    </p>
    <p>
        This means that PN has <alert>twice</alert> the magnitude of <m>\mathbf{PQ}</m>,
        but its direction is <alert>reversed</alert>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="multiplication-vectors-negative-scalar-2">
        <caption></caption>
        <image width="70%">
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>  
            <latex-image>  
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                    
                    \draw[thick,|-] (0,0) -- (2,0);
                    \draw[thick,-|] (2,0) -- (4,0);

                    \draw[thick,|-] (4,0) -- (6,0);
                    \draw[thick,-|] (6,0) -- (8,0);

                    %\draw[thick,|-] (8,0) -- (10,0);
                    %\draw[thick,-|] (10,0) -- (12,0);

                    \node[below] at (0,0) {$\mathbf{P}$};
                    \node[below] at (4,0) {$\mathbf{Q}$};
                    \node[below] at (8,0) {$\mathbf{N}$};

                    \node at (2.5,0.3) {$\mathbf{-a}$};
                    \node at (6.5,0.3) {$\mathbf{-a}$};
                    %\node at (10.5,0.3) {$\mathbf{a}$};
                    
                    % Draw arrows at the middle of the lines
                    \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (2.3,0) -- (2,0);
                    \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (6.3,0) -- (6,0);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image> 
        </image>
    </figure>
    <p> 
        Multiplying a vector by a <alert>negative scalar</alert> reverses its direction,
        making it point in the <alert>opposite direction</alert>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        <alert>Zero Scalar</alert>
    </p>
    <p>
        When a vector <m>\mathbf{a}</m>, as shown in <xref ref="multiplication-vectors-zero-scalar-1"/>,
        is multiplied by <m>0</m>, its magnitude becomes <m>0</m>, resulting in a <alert>zero vector</alert>.
    </p>
    <p>
        <me>
            \mathbf{a} \cdot 0 = 0
        </me>
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="multiplication-vectors-zero-scalar-1">
        <caption></caption>
        <image width="50%">
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>  
            <latex-image>  
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                    
                    \draw[thick,|-|] (0,0) -- (4,0);

                    \node[below] at (0,0) {$\mathbf{P}$};
                    \node[below] at (4,0) {$\mathbf{Q}$};

                    \node at (2,0.4) {$\mathbf{a}$};
                    
                    % Draw arrows at the middle of the lines
                    \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (2,0) -- (2.3,0);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image> 
        </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
        
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>\overrightarrow{AB} = \binom{4}{6}</m>, Find <m>4u</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <m>\overrightarrow{AB} = \binom{4 \times 4}{6 \times 6} = \binom{16}{36}</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
